Express does not break because of the absence of an error handler. It breaks because of ten different ways of responding to an error.
In one controller, you have res.status(404).json({ message }).
In another — throw new Error().
In the third — Prisma throws P2002, Mongoose returns CastError, Zod brings an array of issues, and JWT fails with TokenExpiredError.
As a result, the API starts speaking several dialects at once.
ds-express-errors solves exactly this problem: it brings errors in an Express application to a single format, provides ready-made HTTP presets, can map errors from popular libraries, and does not expose unnecessary information in production.
The current version at the time of this guide is 1.9.0, released on 2026-07-23.

Installation
npm install ds-express-errorsThe minimal integration looks like this:
const express = require('express');
const { errorHandler } = require('ds-express-errors');const app = express();
app.use(express.json());
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
res.json({ ok: true });
});
// errorHandler must always come after routes
app.use(errorHandler);
app.listen(3000, () => {
console.log('Server started on port 3000');
});
The main rule is simple: errorHandler is placed at the very end of the middleware chain. After routes. After controllers. After everything that can call next(err) or throw an error.
If you place it earlier, Express simply will not pass errors from subsequent routes to it.

The Basic Idea
Usually, Express code quickly turns into something like this:
app.get('/users/:id', async (req, res) => {
try {
const user = await User.findById(req.params.id); if (!user) {
return res.status(404).json({
status: 'fail',
message: 'User not found'
});
}
res.json(user);
} catch (err) {
res.status(500).json({
status: 'error',
message: err.message
});
}
});
On a small project, this is tolerable. On a proper API, it is not.
Problems begin quickly:
res.status(400).json({ error: 'Bad request' });
res.status(404).json({ message: 'Not found' });
res.status(500).json({ status: false, data: null });
next(new Error('Something went wrong'));The response format varies. Statuses are selected manually. In production, you can accidentally expose a stack trace or an internal database message. ORMs and validation libraries bring their own error structures.
ds-express-errors offers another approach: the controller reports what happened, while the middleware decides how to return it to the client.

HTTP Presets Instead of Manual Status Codes
The library contains an Errors object with ready-made HTTP presets:
const { Errors } = require('ds-express-errors');app.get('/users/:id', async (req, res, next) => {
const user = await User.findById(req.params.id);
if (!user) {
return next(Errors.NotFound('User not found'));
}
if (!user.isActive) {
return next(Errors.Forbidden('User is not active'));
}
res.json(user);
});
Instead of remembering which status belongs to Conflict or Unprocessable Content, you work with names:
Errors.BadRequest('Invalid payload'); // 400
Errors.Unauthorized('Token is missing'); // 401
Errors.Forbidden('Access denied'); // 403
Errors.NotFound('User not found'); // 404
Errors.Conflict('Email already exists'); // 409
Errors.UnprocessableContent('Invalid fields'); // 422
Errors.TooManyRequests('Rate limit exceeded'); // 429
Errors.InternalServerError(); // 500
Errors.ServiceUnavailable('Database is down'); // 503
Errors.GatewayTimeout('Database timeout'); // 504This is not magic. Each preset returns an AppError with message, statusCode, and isOperational.
For business errors, isOperational is usually true. For unexpected 500 errors, it is false.

AppError for Your Own Cases
If a ready-made preset is not enough, you can create an error directly:
const { AppError } = require('ds-express-errors');throw new AppError('Payment provider rejected request', 402, true);
Format:
new AppError(message, statusCode, isOperational);In practice, presets are usually more convenient. AppError is useful when you need a non-standard status or want to explicitly separate a domain error from a regular Error.

asyncHandler: Less try/catch in Controllers
In async controllers, you constantly have to catch errors and pass them to next.
Without a wrapper:
app.post('/users', async (req, res, next) => {
try {
const user = await User.create(req.body);
res.status(201).json(user);
} catch (err) {
next(err);
}
});With asyncHandler:
const { asyncHandler, Errors } = require('ds-express-errors');app.post('/users', asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
const user = await User.create(req.body);
if (!user) {
throw Errors.BadRequest('User was not created');
}
res.status(201).json(user);
}));
If an exception or rejected promise occurs inside the async function, the wrapper passes the error further to Express. After that, it is handled by errorHandler.
This way, the controller remains a controller. It does not deal with the error format, logging, or a production-safe response.

Default Response Format
In development, the library returns more information:
{
"status": "fail",
"message": "User not found",
"method": "GET",
"url": "/users/123",
"stack": "Error: User not found..."
}In production, the stack, method, and URL are not sent to the client:
{
"status": "fail",
"message": "User not found"
}This is an important boundary.
In development, you need to see where and why everything failed. In production, the client does not need file paths, SQL, a stack trace, or internal validation details.
By default, the development environments are dev and development.

Configuration Through setConfig
setConfig is called before connecting errorHandler.
const express = require('express');
const { setConfig, errorHandler } = require('ds-express-errors');setConfig({
devEnvironments: ['development', 'local'],
formatError: (err, { req, isDev }) => ({
success: false,
error: {
code: err.statusCode,
message: err.message,
...(isDev ? {
method: req.method,
url: req.originalUrl,
stack: err.stack
} : {})
}
})
});
const app = express();
app.use(express.json());
// routes
app.use(errorHandler);
There are several important rules.
setConfig must be called once. This protects the application from a situation where different parts of the project override the error handler’s behavior.
customMappers must be synchronous. Async functions and Promises are not supported. This is intentional: error mapping must be fast and predictable.
formatError is responsible only for the response shape. The status code itself is taken from the error.

Custom Logger
By default, the library uses its own logger. If you already have Winston or Pino, you can pass it:
const { setConfig } = require('ds-express-errors');
const logger = require('./logger');setConfig({
customLogger: logger
});
The logger must support four methods:
{
error() {},
warn() {},
info() {},
debug() {}
}There is also maxLoggerRequests to limit the logging frequency:
setConfig({
maxLoggerRequests: 1000
});If the API has many errors of the same type, this helps prevent the logs from turning into a garbage fire.

Custom Mappers
Sometimes a project has its own errors, for example, from a payment provider, an internal SDK, or a legacy service.
For this, there are customMappers:
const { setConfig, Errors } = require('ds-express-errors');setConfig({
customMappers: [
(err) => {
if (err.code === 'PAYMENT_CARD_DECLINED') {
return Errors.PaymentRequired('Card was declined');
}
},
(err) => {
if (err.name === 'FeatureDisabledError') {
return Errors.Forbidden('Feature is disabled');
}
}
]
});
Custom mappers run before the built-in ones. If a mapper returns an error, the library uses it. If it returns nothing, it continues further.
Do not do this:
setConfig({
customMappers: [
async (err) => {
return Errors.BadRequest('Invalid error');
}
]
});An async mapper will be ignored. Mapping must be synchronous.

Built-In Mappers
The strongest part of the library is the automatic mapping of errors from popular tools.
The following are supported:

• Zod

• Joi

• express-validator

• JWT

• Mongoose / MongoDB

• Prisma

• Sequelize

• JS native errors
For example, a Zod error with issues is turned into an understandable 400 Bad Request.
const { z } = require('zod');
const { asyncHandler } = require('ds-express-errors');const createUserSchema = z.object({
email: z.string().email(),
age: z.number().min(18)
});
app.post('/users', asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
const payload = createUserSchema.parse(req.body);
const user = await User.create(payload);
res.status(201).json(user);
}));
If parse throws a ZodError, you do not need to collect issues manually. The error reaches errorHandler, and it returns a normal HTTP response.
The same applies to JWT:
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');
const { asyncHandler } = require('ds-express-errors');app.get('/me', asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace('Bearer ', '');
const payload = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET);
res.json({ userId: payload.sub });
}));
JsonWebTokenError, TokenExpiredError, and NotBeforeError will be mapped to 401 Unauthorized.

needMappers: Enable Only What You Need
By default, the library uses all available mappers.
If the project uses only Zod and Prisma, you can limit the list:
const { setConfig } = require('ds-express-errors');setConfig({
needMappers: ['zod', 'prisma']
});
Available values:
['zod', 'joi', 'mongoose', 'prisma', 'sequelize', 'expressValidator']This is useful when you want to make the behavior more explicit. For example, if the project does not use Sequelize, there is no point in trying to recognize Sequelize errors.

What Changed in 1.9.0
Version 1.9.0 was released on 2026-07-23.
The main focus of the release is stricter handling of Prisma and Sequelize.
Previously, many libraries had to be identified by the shape of the object: name, code, clientVersion, errors, and meta. This is a working approach, but it always resembles duck typing to some extent. If an object looks like a Prisma error, then it is considered a Prisma error.
In 1.9.0, you can pass the actual error classes through errorClasses.
const { setConfig } = require('ds-express-errors');
const { Prisma } = require('@prisma/client');
const { Sequelize } = require('sequelize');setConfig({
errorClasses: {
Prisma,
Sequelize
}
});
After this, Prisma and Sequelize can be checked through instanceof, not only by a similar object structure.
This is especially useful in large projects where errors can come from different layers: ORMs, SDKs, queues, external clients, and internal packages. The stricter the check, the lower the chance that a random object will be mapped to the wrong error.
In 1.9.0, important details were also fixed and improved:

• Fixed ESM import error

• Fixed PrismaClientInitializationError detection

• Improved SequelizeConnectionError detection

• Improved Prisma and Sequelize dev log output
For Sequelize, connection-related errors are now distinguished more accurately:

• SequelizeConnectionRefusedError

• SequelizeHostNotFoundError

• SequelizeHostNotReachableError

• SequelizeAccessDeniedError
In practice, this helps you understand more quickly what exactly happened: the database is unavailable, the host was not found, access was denied, or the connection was refused.

Prisma Example
With Prisma, you most often want to handle P2002, P2025, P1001, and similar errors properly.
const { PrismaClient, Prisma } = require('@prisma/client');
const { setConfig, asyncHandler } = require('ds-express-errors');const prisma = new PrismaClient();
setConfig({
errorClasses: {
Prisma
},
needMappers: ['prisma']
});
app.post('/users', asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
const user = await prisma.user.create({
data: {
email: req.body.email,
name: req.body.name
}
});
res.status(201).json(user);
}));
If the email is unique and Prisma throws P2002, the library will return 409 Conflict.
If a record is not found through a scenario that results in P2
